results.notes:
A single young specimen with extensive slug-fest damage growing under a mature oak in mixed deciduous woods (oaks and beech in this area). It is probably the same species as obs 431917, which was found 40-50 yards to the SSE from the present collection earlier on the same day. This lovely porcini s.s. appears to be a widespread entity in the local section of the woods, where many trees are in close proximity to each other and are thus likely to host the mushroom’s mycelium — see MO431917 for the previous posts of this taxon from that area.
One interesting feature seen in this young collection, but not the other ones, is the whitish bloom on the cap surface. I didn’t notice it when handing the mushroom, but became aware of it while processing the photos.
This collection will be sampled for ITS to see if it’s the same species/organism as obs 244398; the latter was found ~80 yards away to the SSE 4 year ago.

results.notes:
Collected by Dave W at the NJMA foray. Dave has already posted it as obs 426025.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 26-Feb-23):
This collection was sampled for ITS by Dr. Kudzma. The targeted amplicon was ITS1F ==> LR22, meaning that a full-length ITS and the first 300+ bps of LSU should have been procured as a contiguous sequence under ideal conditions, with at least some overlap between the reads. However, due to unknown technical issues affecting a good number of samples processed late last year, many generated reads came out short/truncated.
In this case, the forward read delivered just the first 230 bps of ITS (5’ end) before the peaks disappeared into the noisy baseline, and the reverse read barely crossed into the 3’ end of ITS2 before the same thing happened. Thus the two reads cannot be connected. The two fragments are posted to this obsie.
Still, despite this shortcoming, the short reads are long enough for publication in GenBank. The forward read matches Steve Russell’s recently deposited accessions labeled as “Xerocomus tenax” (OM972656 & OP643298) with 99.5-100% similarity. The similarity then drops to 96.5% for the 3rd hit from the top that happens to belong to obs 326544, which is clearly a different species.
Since Steve, Dave and I are in agreement here regarding the identity of this taxon as X. tenax, there is a good chance we got the species concept right. Of course, a sequence from the type collection would be nice to have for comparison.
